ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='The dashboard_api.js does handle missing files gracefully — it return
s fallback data. So even if `agents/grace/output/` files are missing, the API wi
ll still work.\n\nFor the ECS Fargate deployment, I can create Dockerfiles that 
copy the necessary code and create empty output directories. The scheduler will 
generate `trade_signals.json` into the shared volume.\n\nNow, the key design dec
ision: single task vs multiple tasks.\n\n**Single Task with 3 Containers:**\n- P
ros: Cheapest (~$18/month), shared ephemeral storage, simple\n- Cons: All contai
ners scale together, if one crashes the whole task restarts\n- Task size: 512 CP
U / 1024 MB\n\n**Separate Tasks:**\n- Pros: Independent scaling/restart, better 
isolation\n- Cons: More expensive (~$36/month without spot), need shared storage
(EFS) for trade_signals.json\n\nGiven Alice\'s cost target of ~$29/month, I\'ll 
design a **single ECS task with 3 containers** as the primary deployment. I\'ll 
also note in the runbook that this can be split into separate tasks later if nee
ded.\n\nBut wait — Alice said "ECS Fargate — kalshi-dashboard (port 3200), kalsh
i-scheduler, kalshi-monitor". This could be interpreted as 3 separate ECS servic
es. However, the cost constraint strongly suggests a single task.\n\nActually, I
can design it as 3 separate services but with Fargate Spot for scheduler and mon
itor to hit the ~$29 target:\n- Dashboard: 256 CPU / 512 MB regular Fargate = ~$
9/month\n- Scheduler: 256 CPU / 512 MB Fargate Spot = ~$3/month\n- Monitor: 256 
CPU / 512 MB Fargate Spot = ~$3/month\n- ALB: ~$16/month minimum\n- Total: ~$31/
month\n\nWithout ALB (using public IP for dashboard):\n- Dashboard: ~$9/month\n-
Scheduler: ~$3/month\n- Monitor: ~$3/month\n- Total: ~$15/month\n\nBut then how 
do the scheduler and monitor communicate with the dashboard? They don\'t need to
— the monitor checks port 3100 (which is a bug we found earlier) or some health 
endpoint. Actually, the monitor.js checks localhost:3100 which won\'t work in se
parate tasks.\n\nWait, if they\'re in separate tasks, `localhost:3100` won\'t wo
rk. The monitor would need to check the dashboard service\'s IP or use the task\
's private IP.\n\nIf they\'re in the same task, `localhost:3100` still won\'t wo
rk because the dashboard is on port 3200, not 3100. But at least they share the 
same network namespace and can use `localhost:3200`.\n\nActually, looking at mon
itor.js again, it checks `strategyApiPort: 3100`. This is a hardcoded port that 
nothing listens on. So the monitor is currently broken regardless of deployment 
architecture. I\'ve already reported this to Liam.\n\nFor the ECS deployment, I 
should configure the monitor to check `localhost:3200` (the dashboard API) or ju
st let it run as-is knowing it has a bug. But I shouldn\'t modify Liam\'s code.\
n\nActually, I can pass `STRATEGY_API_PORT=3200` as an environment variable if t
he monitor supports it. Let me check.',
